<?php

namespace Database\Seeders;

use App\Models\Platform;
use App\Models\PlatformComparison;
use Illuminate\Database\Seeder;

/**
 * 30 high-search-volume platform comparisons (21 exchange pairs + 9 wallet
 * pairs — same-category comparisons only, an exchange-vs-wallet pairing
 * isn't a meaningful "vs"). Every verdict is original, nuanced prose with
 * no invented numbers and an explicit disclaimer — see DISCLAIMER below.
 *
 * Idempotent: each pair is checked for existence (in canonical
 * lower-id-first order, so "Binance vs Bybit" and "Bybit vs Binance" can
 * never both exist) before creating — re-running this never duplicates or
 * overwrites a pair, including one edited by hand afterwards in Filament.
 */
class PlatformComparisonSeeder extends Seeder
{
    private const DISCLAIMER = '<p class="text-xs text-slate-500 mt-3"><em>This comparison is for informational purposes only and is not financial advice. Always verify current fees, supported regions and licensing directly with each platform before deciding.</em></p>';

    public function run(): void
    {
        // Safe to call even if already run — PlatformSeeder is idempotent.
        $this->call(PlatformSeeder::class);

        foreach ($this->pairs() as [$slugA, $slugB, $verdict]) {
            $requestedA = Platform::where('slug', $slugA)->first();
            $requestedB = Platform::where('slug', $slugB)->first();

            if (! $requestedA || ! $requestedB) {
                $this->command?->warn("Skipping {$slugA} vs {$slugB} — one or both platforms not found.");
                continue;
            }

            // Canonicalize by id so "A vs B" and "B vs A" are always the
            // same row, regardless of which order they're listed below.
            [$a, $b] = $requestedA->id < $requestedB->id
                ? [$requestedA, $requestedB]
                : [$requestedB, $requestedA];

            $exists = PlatformComparison::where('platform_a_id', $a->id)
                ->where('platform_b_id', $b->id)
                ->exists();

            if ($exists) {
                continue;
            }

            PlatformComparison::create([
                'platform_a_id' => $a->id,
                'platform_b_id' => $b->id,
                // Slug follows the order written below (not the canonical
                // id order) so URLs read naturally, e.g. ledger-vs-trezor.
                'slug' => "{$requestedA->slug}-vs-{$requestedB->slug}",
                'verdict_html' => $verdict.self::DISCLAIMER,
                'meta_title' => "{$requestedA->name} vs {$requestedB->name}: Which Should You Choose?",
                'meta_description' => "An honest, side-by-side comparison of {$requestedA->name} and {$requestedB->name} — who each one is best for, and what to weigh before choosing.",
                'status' => 'published',
                'published_at' => now()->subDay(),
            ]);
        }
    }

    /** @return array<int, array{0: string, 1: string, 2: string}> */
    private function pairs(): array
    {
        return [
            // ── Exchanges (21 pairs) ────────────────────────────────────
            ['binance', 'bybit', '<p>Binance and Bybit are both large centralized exchanges with strong liquidity, but they lead in different areas. Binance generally offers the widest coin selection and deepest overall liquidity, making it a common default for spot trading across many assets. Bybit has built a strong reputation specifically around derivatives and futures trading, with a trading experience many active traders find responsive on both mobile and web.</p><p>Beginners looking for the broadest simple spot market will likely find Binance\'s range convenient, while traders focused specifically on futures or perpetual contracts often gravitate to Bybit. Both require identity verification for full account limits and have faced varying regulatory treatment across different countries, so checking availability in your own jurisdiction is essential before signing up. Neither platform is inherently "better" — the right choice depends heavily on whether your priority is spot market breadth or derivatives-focused trading tools.</p>'],
            ['binance', 'okx', '<p>Binance and OKX both offer extensive spot and derivatives markets, but the experience diverges once you look past the basics. Binance\'s scale generally translates into deeper liquidity and one of the widest coin selections available on a centralized exchange. OKX distinguishes itself with a built-in Web3 wallet and DeFi access alongside its trading platform, appealing to users who want to move between centralized trading and on-chain activity without switching apps.</p><p>Both platforms offer advanced order types and derivatives products aimed at experienced traders, and both can feel dense for someone opening their first crypto account. Regulatory availability differs by country for each exchange, and neither should be assumed to be licensed where you live without checking directly. If integrated Web3/DeFi access matters to you, OKX has an edge; if raw market breadth and liquidity matter more, Binance is generally the safer default.</p>'],
            ['binance', 'coinbase', '<p>Binance and Coinbase sit at opposite ends of the trade-off between breadth and regulatory simplicity. Binance lists a far wider range of cryptocurrencies and generally offers more advanced trading tools, appealing to users who want access to smaller-cap coins or more sophisticated order types. Coinbase, as a publicly traded, US-headquartered company, is often chosen by beginners and US-based users specifically for its regulatory transparency and straightforward interface.</p><p>That simplicity typically comes with a narrower coin selection and, historically, higher fees than many international competitors — always confirm current pricing directly, as fee structures change. Coinbase\'s long operating history and public listing give it a particular kind of transparency that offshore exchanges don\'t offer in the same way. If you\'re a first-time US buyer prioritizing ease of use and regulatory clarity, Coinbase is a common starting point; if you want the widest possible market access, Binance offers more depth.</p>'],
            ['binance', 'kraken', '<p>Binance and Kraken are both long-established exchanges, but they\'re often chosen for different reasons. Binance\'s main draw is scale — a very wide selection of listed coins and generally strong liquidity across spot and derivatives markets. Kraken has built its reputation largely around security and reliability, with no major user-fund hack on record since it launched in 2011, and support for a wide range of fiat currencies for deposits and withdrawals.</p><p>Kraken also offers both a simplified interface and a more advanced "Pro" platform for experienced traders, though the advanced version has a real learning curve. Binance tends to list newer and smaller-cap coins faster than Kraken does. Availability varies by US state and by country for both exchanges, so confirm access in your region first. Users prioritizing a long, clean security track record often lean toward Kraken; those prioritizing coin selection and trading volume often lean toward Binance.</p>'],
            ['binance', 'kucoin', '<p>Binance and KuCoin both list a large number of cryptocurrencies, but they serve somewhat different audiences. Binance generally has deeper liquidity for major coins and a more mainstream reputation, while KuCoin has built its identity around listing smaller and newer altcoins earlier than many larger competitors, along with allowing limited trading before completing full identity verification.</p><p>That altcoin breadth is a double-edged sword: many of the tokens available on KuCoin are lower-liquidity and inherently higher risk than the large-cap assets that dominate Binance\'s volume. KuCoin has also faced regulatory action in some jurisdictions, which is worth researching before committing significant funds. Neither exchange should be assumed to be licensed in every country — check local availability first. If you\'re mainly trading major cryptocurrencies, Binance\'s liquidity is likely the safer choice; if you\'re specifically hunting for early access to smaller altcoins, KuCoin\'s listings are broader, at correspondingly higher risk.</p>'],
            ['binance', 'bitget', '<p>Binance and Bitget both offer a wide range of spot and derivatives products, but Bitget has carved out a specific niche around copy-trading and social trading features that let users mirror the trades of other, often more experienced, traders. Binance, by contrast, is a broader, longer-established platform with generally deeper liquidity and a much larger overall user base.</p><p>Bitget\'s copy-trading tools can be appealing to newer traders who want exposure to active strategies without managing every trade themselves, but this adds a layer of risk beyond ordinary market risk — copying a losing trader\'s strategy loses money just as directly as making the trade yourself. Bitget\'s operating history is shorter than Binance\'s, and its regulatory licensing varies by region. If copy-trading specifically is what you\'re after, Bitget is more purpose-built for it; for general spot and derivatives trading with maximum liquidity, Binance remains the larger, more established option.</p>'],
            ['bybit', 'okx', '<p>Bybit and OKX are both exchanges with a strong focus on derivatives and futures trading, and the choice between them often comes down to secondary features rather than core trading functionality. OKX stands out for its integrated Web3 wallet and DeFi access, letting users move between centralized trading and on-chain activity in one app — a feature Bybit doesn\'t offer in the same way. Bybit is generally seen as having a clean, responsive trading interface across mobile and web, with a large and active derivatives trading community.</p><p>Both exchanges carry the elevated risk inherent to leveraged and derivatives products, which is not suitable for every trader. Licensing and availability differ by country for both platforms and can change, so check current regional restrictions before signing up. If on-chain/DeFi integration matters to you alongside trading, OKX has the edge; if you want a dedicated derivatives-trading experience, Bybit is a strong, purpose-built option.</p>'],
            ['bybit', 'coinbase', '<p>Bybit and Coinbase serve quite different audiences, which makes this less a head-to-head and more a question of what you actually need. Coinbase is a publicly traded, US-headquartered exchange best known for regulatory transparency and a beginner-friendly interface, with a product lineup generally aimed at straightforward spot buying and holding. Bybit is built around active trading, particularly derivatives and futures, with tools aimed at more experienced traders and a global user base outside the more conservative US retail product set.</p><p>Bybit has also not been licensed or available in every market, including periods of restricted access in the US, so regional availability is worth confirming directly. Coinbase\'s public listing gives it a level of regulatory visibility that offshore exchanges don\'t share. If you\'re new to crypto and want a simple, regulated entry point, Coinbase is the more conventional choice; if you\'re an experienced trader seeking derivatives tools, Bybit is more purpose-built for that.</p>'],
            ['bybit', 'kraken', '<p>Bybit and Kraken appeal to different priorities. Kraken has built its reputation over more than a decade largely around security and reliability, with no major user-fund hack on record and support for a wide range of fiat currencies. Bybit\'s strength lies more in its derivatives and futures trading tools, with a trading experience many active traders find responsive, though this comes with the elevated risk that leveraged products carry generally.</p><p>Kraken offers both a simplified interface for newcomers and a more advanced "Pro" platform, while Bybit\'s product lineup leans more consistently toward active and derivatives trading throughout. Regional licensing differs for each exchange and has shifted over time, including periods where Bybit was not accessible in some markets — always check current availability where you live. If a long, clean security track record and fiat flexibility matter most, Kraken is the steadier choice; if active derivatives trading is the goal, Bybit is more specialized for it.</p>'],
            ['bybit', 'kucoin', '<p>Bybit and KuCoin both offer a wide range of trading products, but they lead with different strengths. Bybit is most associated with derivatives and futures trading and a responsive trading interface, while KuCoin has built its identity around listing a very broad range of smaller and newer altcoins, with the option to trade in a limited capacity before completing full identity verification.</p><p>KuCoin\'s altcoin breadth means many of its listed tokens carry lower liquidity and higher risk than the larger-cap assets more central to Bybit\'s volume. Both exchanges have faced regulatory questions in various jurisdictions and are not licensed everywhere, so confirming access in your own country is an important first step. If you\'re focused on derivatives and futures specifically, Bybit\'s tools are more purpose-built; if you\'re hunting for early access to a wide range of altcoins, KuCoin\'s listings go further, with correspondingly higher risk.</p>'],
            ['bybit', 'bitget', '<p>Bybit and Bitget both compete heavily in the derivatives and futures space, but Bitget has leaned further into copy-trading and social trading features, letting users automatically mirror other traders\' positions. Bybit\'s derivatives platform is broader and has a longer track record, with a trading interface many active users find responsive across devices.</p><p>Bitget\'s copy-trading tools can lower the barrier to entry for newer traders wanting exposure to active strategies, but they add a layer of risk beyond normal market risk, since a followed trader\'s losses become your losses too. Both platforms run frequent promotional trading incentives, which are worth reading the terms of carefully rather than treating as free money. Licensing and regional availability vary for both and change over time. If copy-trading is specifically what you want, Bitget is more purpose-built for it; for broader, longer-established derivatives trading, Bybit is the more established option.</p>'],
            ['okx', 'coinbase', '<p>OKX and Coinbase sit at different points on the trade-off between advanced functionality and regulatory simplicity. OKX offers a broad spot and derivatives market alongside a built-in Web3 wallet and DeFi access, aimed at users comfortable navigating a more feature-dense platform. Coinbase, as a publicly traded, US-headquartered company, is generally the more beginner-friendly and regulatorily transparent option, with a simpler product set focused on straightforward buying, selling and holding.</p><p>That simplicity on Coinbase\'s side typically comes with a narrower coin selection and, historically, higher fees than many international exchanges — confirm current pricing directly rather than assuming. OKX\'s licensing and availability vary by region and it is restricted in some markets, including historically limited US access. If you want deep trading tools and on-chain integration and your region supports it, OKX offers more; if you want a simple, US-regulated entry point, Coinbase remains the more conventional choice.</p>'],
            ['okx', 'kraken', '<p>OKX and Kraken both offer advanced trading tools, but they\'re known for different strengths. Kraken\'s reputation rests heavily on its long security track record, with no major user-fund hack on record since 2011, plus support for a wide range of fiat currencies. OKX distinguishes itself with a built-in Web3 wallet and DeFi access alongside its trading platform, useful for users who want to move between centralized trading and on-chain activity in one place.</p><p>Both platforms offer a simplified mode alongside more advanced trading tools, and both carry a learning curve once you move past basic buying and selling. Regional availability differs for each exchange and is worth checking directly, as licensing status can change over time. If a long, clean security history is your top priority, Kraken has the stronger track record; if integrated Web3/DeFi functionality matters more to you, OKX offers that in a way Kraken currently does not.</p>'],
            ['okx', 'kucoin', '<p>OKX and KuCoin both list a wide range of trading pairs, but for different reasons. OKX\'s breadth comes with a strong focus on derivatives and an integrated Web3 wallet, aimed at traders who want advanced tools in one place. KuCoin\'s breadth leans more toward listing smaller and newer altcoins earlier than many competitors, along with allowing limited trading before full identity verification is completed.</p><p>That means KuCoin\'s listings skew toward lower-liquidity, higher-risk tokens more often than OKX\'s core markets do. Both exchanges have faced regulatory questions in different jurisdictions at different times, and neither is licensed everywhere — confirm availability in your own country before signing up. If advanced trading tools and on-chain integration are the priority, OKX is the more purpose-built option; if early access to a wide range of altcoins matters more, KuCoin\'s listings go further, at correspondingly higher risk.</p>'],
            ['okx', 'bitget', '<p>OKX and Bitget both offer derivatives-heavy trading platforms, but they differentiate through different secondary features. OKX pairs its trading platform with a built-in Web3 wallet and DeFi access, useful for users who want centralized trading and on-chain activity in one app. Bitget has instead focused on copy-trading and social trading tools that let users mirror other traders\' positions automatically.</p><p>Copy-trading can lower the effort required to get started with active trading, but it introduces its own risk — you inherit the losses of whoever you\'re copying, not just market risk generally. Bitget\'s operating history is shorter than OKX\'s, and both platforms\' licensing and regional availability vary and can change. If integrated Web3/DeFi functionality is what you want alongside trading, OKX is more purpose-built for that; if you specifically want to try copy-trading, Bitget offers more developed tools for it, understanding the added layer of risk involved.</p>'],
            ['coinbase', 'kraken', '<p>Coinbase and Kraken are two of the longer-established, US-headquartered exchanges, and both are commonly recommended as relatively conservative starting points. Coinbase is publicly traded (Nasdaq: COIN) and generally regarded as the more beginner-friendly of the two, with a simple interface aimed at straightforward buying and holding. Kraken has built its reputation more specifically around security, with no major user-fund hack on record since launching in 2011, and it supports a wider range of fiat currencies for deposits and withdrawals than many competitors.</p><p>Kraken also offers a more advanced "Pro" trading interface for experienced users, alongside its simpler mode. Both platforms have historically charged higher fees than some offshore competitors — always confirm current pricing directly. Neither is available in every US state. If ease of use and public-company transparency matter most, Coinbase is the more conventional pick; if a long security track record and fiat flexibility matter more, Kraken has the edge.</p>'],
            ['coinbase', 'kucoin', '<p>Coinbase and KuCoin sit at nearly opposite ends of the regulatory-transparency-versus-coin-breadth trade-off. Coinbase is a publicly traded, US-headquartered exchange known for regulatory transparency and a simple, beginner-friendly interface, but with a comparatively narrow coin selection. KuCoin lists a much wider range of smaller and newer altcoins and allows limited trading before full identity verification, but it has faced regulatory action in some jurisdictions and carries a different risk profile as a result.</p><p>If you\'re a beginner or a US-based user who values regulatory clarity above all else, Coinbase is the more conventional starting point. If you\'re specifically looking for early access to a broad range of altcoins and are comfortable with the added risk that comes with lower-liquidity tokens and less regulatory certainty, KuCoin offers more of that. Neither platform\'s fee structure should be assumed without checking current rates directly, and availability varies by country for both.</p>'],
            ['coinbase', 'bitget', '<p>Coinbase and Bitget are aimed at fairly different types of users. Coinbase is a publicly traded, US-headquartered exchange focused on straightforward spot buying and holding, with a simple interface that\'s generally considered friendly to first-time users. Bitget is built more around active and derivatives trading, with copy-trading and social trading tools that let users mirror other traders\' positions.</p><p>Bitget\'s copy-trading feature can make active trading more approachable, but it adds risk beyond ordinary market exposure, since you inherit losses from whoever you\'re copying. Bitget\'s operating history is shorter than Coinbase\'s, and its regulatory licensing varies significantly by region compared to Coinbase\'s US public-company status. If you want a simple, regulated entry point for buying and holding crypto, Coinbase is the more conventional option; if you\'re interested in active or copy-trading with derivatives exposure, Bitget offers tools built specifically for that, at correspondingly higher risk.</p>'],
            ['kraken', 'kucoin', '<p>Kraken and KuCoin represent different priorities within the exchange market. Kraken has built its reputation over more than a decade largely around security, with no major user-fund hack on record and support for a wide range of fiat currencies. KuCoin instead emphasizes breadth of altcoin listings, often adding smaller and newer tokens earlier than larger competitors, and it allows limited trading before completing full identity verification.</p><p>That breadth comes with trade-offs: many tokens on KuCoin are lower-liquidity and higher-risk than the assets that dominate Kraken\'s markets, and KuCoin has faced regulatory action in some jurisdictions. Kraken also offers both a simplified interface and a more advanced "Pro" platform for experienced traders. Regional availability differs for both exchanges. If a long, conservative security track record matters most to you, Kraken is the steadier option; if you specifically want early access to a wide range of altcoins, KuCoin\'s listings go further, at correspondingly higher risk.</p>'],
            ['kraken', 'bitget', '<p>Kraken and Bitget appeal to quite different trading styles. Kraken\'s core strength is its long security track record, with no major user-fund hack on record since 2011, alongside support for a wide range of fiat currencies and both simple and advanced trading interfaces. Bitget instead leans heavily into derivatives and copy-trading, letting users mirror other traders\' positions automatically — a feature that can lower the barrier to active trading but introduces the added risk of inheriting a copied trader\'s losses.</p><p>Bitget\'s operating history is considerably shorter than Kraken\'s, and its regulatory licensing varies more by region. If a long-established, security-focused exchange is your priority, Kraken has the stronger track record; if you\'re specifically interested in derivatives trading or trying copy-trading tools, Bitget is more purpose-built for that, with the understanding that both derivatives and copy-trading carry meaningfully elevated risk compared to simple spot buying and holding.</p>'],
            ['kucoin', 'bitget', '<p>KuCoin and Bitget both offer a wide range of products beyond simple spot trading, but with different specialties. KuCoin is most known for its broad altcoin listings and for allowing limited trading before completing full identity verification, appealing to users hunting for early access to smaller-cap tokens. Bitget is built more around derivatives and copy-trading, letting users mirror other traders\' positions automatically.</p><p>Both carry real, distinct risks: KuCoin\'s altcoin breadth includes many lower-liquidity, higher-risk tokens, while Bitget\'s copy-trading and derivatives products expose users to losses beyond what simple spot trading would. Both exchanges have shorter or more mixed regulatory track records than the largest, longest-established platforms, and licensing varies by region for each. If early altcoin access is your goal, KuCoin\'s listings are broader; if derivatives and copy-trading tools are what you\'re after, Bitget is more purpose-built for that — either way, position sizing and research matter more here than on more conservative platforms.</p>'],

            // ── Wallets (9 pairs) ───────────────────────────────────────
            ['ledger', 'trezor', '<p>Ledger and Trezor are the two most established hardware wallet brands, and the comparison usually comes down to ecosystem and coin support rather than core security, since both store private keys offline on a dedicated device. Ledger, made by a French company, generally supports a wider range of cryptocurrencies through its Ledger Live app and has sold more units cumulatively. Trezor, made by Czech company SatoshiLabs, was the original mass-market hardware wallet, launching in 2014, and it emphasizes open-source firmware and software components more than Ledger does.</p><p>Neither wallet requires identity verification to use, since they\'re self-custody tools rather than accounts. Both require buying a physical device, and both carry the same fundamental risk: losing the device and your recovery phrase together means permanent loss of funds, with no company able to recover it for you. If open-source transparency matters most to you, Trezor has the edge; if broader coin support matters more, Ledger currently offers more.</p>'],
            ['ledger', 'tangem', '<p>Ledger and Tangem take different approaches to hardware wallet design. Ledger uses a more traditional hardware wallet form factor with a screen, supporting a very wide range of coins through its Ledger Live app and backed by a long track record with millions of units sold. Tangem instead ships as a set of credit-card-shaped devices with no screen and no battery, aimed at users who want the simplest possible physical wallet experience, with an optional backup card replacing a traditionally written seed phrase.</p><p>That simplicity is also a trade-off: without an on-device screen, Tangem users can\'t independently verify transaction details the way Ledger\'s screen allows. Tangem is also considerably newer to the market, with a shorter track record than Ledger\'s. Neither requires identity verification to use. If you want the most established option with the widest coin support, Ledger is the safer default; if simplicity and physical durability matter most, Tangem\'s card format is purpose-built for that.</p>'],
            ['trezor', 'tangem', '<p>Trezor and Tangem represent two different philosophies of hardware wallet design. Trezor uses a traditional device with a screen, open-source firmware, and a track record going back to 2014, letting users independently verify transaction details on-device before approving them. Tangem instead ships as screenless, card-shaped devices designed for simplicity, with an optional backup card in place of a written seed phrase, but without the ability to visually confirm transaction details on the device itself the way Trezor allows.</p><p>Tangem is meaningfully newer to the market, so it has a shorter independent track record than Trezor\'s roughly decade-plus history. Neither wallet requires identity verification, since both are self-custody tools. If on-device transaction verification and an established, open-source track record matter most to you, Trezor is the more conservative choice; if you want the simplest possible physical setup and don\'t mind giving up the on-screen verification step, Tangem\'s card format is built specifically for that.</p>'],
            ['ledger', 'metamask', '<p>Ledger and MetaMask are often used together rather than as pure alternatives, but the comparison matters if you\'re deciding where your private keys actually live. Ledger is a hardware wallet that keeps keys offline on a physical device, which generally makes it more resistant to malware and phishing than a purely software-based option. MetaMask is a free browser extension and mobile app that stores keys on your device software, offering more convenience for frequent interaction with Ethereum and EVM-compatible dApps, but with more exposure to the risks that come with any internet-connected software.</p><p>In practice, many users pair the two: MetaMask as the interface, connected to a Ledger device for signing transactions, combining convenience with offline key storage. On their own, MetaMask is free and instantly available, while Ledger requires buying and setting up a physical device. If security for larger holdings is the priority, hardware storage is generally considered safer; for everyday small-value dApp interaction, MetaMask alone is more convenient.</p>'],
            ['ledger', 'trust-wallet', '<p>Ledger and Trust Wallet sit on different sides of the cold-storage-versus-convenience trade-off. Ledger keeps private keys offline on dedicated hardware, which generally offers stronger protection against malware and remote attacks, at the cost of needing to buy and carry a physical device. Trust Wallet is a free mobile app, developed by Binance, that supports a very large number of blockchains and includes a built-in dApp browser and swap feature, prioritizing convenience and mobile-first access over offline key storage.</p><p>Neither requires identity verification to use, since both are self-custody wallets. Trust Wallet\'s software-based nature means it\'s more exposed to device-level risks like malware than Ledger\'s offline storage, though it\'s considerably easier to start using immediately at no cost. Some users treat these as complementary rather than competing: smaller, active balances in Trust Wallet, larger long-term holdings on a Ledger device. If maximum security for significant holdings is the goal, Ledger is the stronger choice; for everyday multi-chain convenience, Trust Wallet is easier to use.</p>'],
            ['trezor', 'metamask', '<p>Trezor and MetaMask are frequently used together, but comparing them directly comes down to where your keys are stored and how much convenience you\'re willing to trade for security. Trezor is a hardware wallet with open-source firmware that keeps keys offline and lets you verify transaction details on the device\'s own screen before approving anything. MetaMask is a free browser extension and mobile app that\'s more convenient for frequent Ethereum/EVM dApp use, but it stores keys in software, making it more exposed to malware and phishing than an offline device.</p><p>Many users connect MetaMask to a Trezor device specifically to combine MetaMask\'s dApp compatibility with Trezor\'s offline key storage and on-device verification. Used alone, MetaMask is free and instant to set up, while Trezor requires purchasing hardware. For securing significant holdings, hardware storage is generally the more conservative approach; for quick, low-value dApp interactions, MetaMask alone is simpler and sufficient for many users.</p>'],
            ['trezor', 'trust-wallet', '<p>Trezor and Trust Wallet represent different priorities: offline security versus everyday mobile convenience. Trezor is a hardware wallet with open-source firmware, keeping private keys offline and letting users verify transactions on the device\'s own screen — a meaningful protection against remote malware that purely software-based wallets don\'t have. Trust Wallet is a free mobile app, developed by Binance, supporting a very wide range of blockchains with a built-in dApp browser and swap feature, prioritizing ease of use over offline storage.</p><p>Neither wallet requires identity verification, since both are self-custody tools rather than exchange accounts. Trust Wallet\'s software-based design means it carries more exposure to device-level threats than Trezor\'s offline hardware, but it\'s free and immediately usable without buying anything. Many users keep smaller, actively used balances in a mobile wallet like Trust Wallet while storing larger holdings on a hardware device like Trezor. For significant long-term holdings, hardware storage is the more conservative choice; for daily multi-chain use, Trust Wallet is more convenient.</p>'],
            ['metamask', 'trust-wallet', '<p>MetaMask and Trust Wallet are both free, self-custody software wallets, and the choice between them usually comes down to chain support and ecosystem fit rather than security, since both store keys on your device rather than offline. MetaMask is more tightly focused on Ethereum and EVM-compatible chains, with the broadest dApp compatibility in that ecosystem, originally built as a browser extension before adding a mobile app. Trust Wallet, developed by Binance, supports a notably larger number of blockchains out of the box, including many non-EVM chains, and has been mobile-first from the start with a built-in dApp browser and swap feature.</p><p>Neither requires identity verification to install and use. Both carry the same fundamental software-wallet risk: no company can recover a lost seed phrase, and being internet-connected software makes both more exposed to malware and phishing than a hardware wallet. If your activity is concentrated on Ethereum/EVM dApps, MetaMask has the deeper ecosystem support; if you need broad multi-chain coverage in one app, Trust Wallet supports more networks natively.</p>'],
            ['tangem', 'trust-wallet', '<p>Tangem and Trust Wallet take very different approaches to wallet security, despite both aiming to be simple and accessible. Tangem is a screenless, card-shaped hardware wallet that keeps keys offline on the physical card itself, requiring a tap against a phone to sign transactions, with an optional backup card instead of a written seed phrase. Trust Wallet is a free mobile app that stores keys in software on your device, supporting a very large number of blockchains along with a built-in dApp browser and swap feature.</p><p>Because Tangem stores keys offline on dedicated hardware, it\'s generally more resistant to malware than a software wallet like Trust Wallet, though it requires purchasing physical cards and has a shorter market track record than more established wallets. Neither requires identity verification to use. If offline key storage matters most to you and you want the simplest possible hardware setup, Tangem is purpose-built for that; if you want a free, highly flexible multi-chain app, Trust Wallet is easier to start with immediately.</p>'],
        ];
    }
}
